This package contains the design inputs for the %#NewPhysicalArchModule#% . The %#NewPhysicalArchModule#% package is used to define the behaviors, specs, and architecture that is needed for the new module. The %#NewPhysicalArchModule#% Package provides the high level description for the module that needs to be incorporated into the detailed design. The package contains:
  1. Inputs Canvas
  2. Module Functions
  3. Design Specs and Reqs Analysis
  4. Use Cases
  5. Design Analysis
  6. Test Cases

The flow down from System to Subsystem to Design Specs is important to capture as the context for which the requirements were created should be considered when creating the design specs. The Design Spec and Requirements Analysis package is contains the requirements flow down for the %#NewPhysicalArchModule#%.

Use cases are created to describe the various uses of the module from the actors perspective. The Use Cases herein are specifically written to capture the behaviors of the %#NewPhysicalArchModule#%. Module Use Cases are intended to show the detailed behaviors of the %#NewPhysicalArchModule#%. The use case process for %#NewPhysicalArchModule#% is recursively iterative decomposing use cases to break %#NewPhysicalArchModule#% into parts.

The functions package contains the breakdown of the subsystem functions into the functions that the module needs to fulfill. This package encapsulates a comprehensive set of functions that are derived from the broader system and subsystem functions, ensuring a seamless traceability and alignment with the overarching system architecture. Each function within this package is meticulously documented, highlighting its origin from system-level and subsystem-level requirements, and illustrating its role in fulfilling the module's operational capabilities.
This canvas is created to show the key design attributes for %#NewPhysicalArchModule#% which need to be considered when parts are selected to fulfill the functions required by the module.

Complex modules require iterative design and testing, which is often used to design, implement, and test the behaviors of design concepts relative to the user's expectations. With each passing iteration additional functions are implemented to test the behaviors of the module against increasing expectations. This diagram shows the generations at which each use case is planed. Thinking and evaluating modules behaviors in this method enables us to pause development when behaviors (expectations) are achieved. Implementation is set based upon the MoSCoW Prioritization scale.

The %#NewPhysicalArchModule#% shows the functional requirements flowed down from the subsystem to the %#NewPhysicalArchModule#% module. This diagram is useful we relating the functional allocations from system to subsystem, to module.

An IPO (Input-Process-Output) Diagram is a high-level diagram used for systems analysis that visually describes business processes with the description of each function in words shown from the implementation perspective. An IPO diagram shows a process's key inputs and resulting outputs after a set of functions. The IPO analysis concept was extended for %#NewPhysicalArchModule#% for functional analysis by using the Hatley and Pirbhai (H-P) for real-time control systems. The %#NewPhysicalArchModule#% functional decomposition used the (H-P) IPO analysis technique shown in the diagram. <font color="#0000ff"> </font><font color="#0000ff">The Functional Flow Block Diagram package provides a general construct to systematically identify, describe and relate the functions performed by either the user or system to meet their goal. </font> <font color="#0000ff"> </font><font color="#0000ff">A user FFBD helps with understanding what users are going to do. The System Functional Flow block diagram is a very useful tool in describing the top level functions that need to be performed by the system. </font> <font color="#0000ff"> </font><font color="#0000ff">A functional flow block diagram is functionally oriented only and can be used as a starting point to map out order of operations or logic flow which can then be decomposed to define the system functional design and interfaces.</font>

This diagram shows the prioritization of the %#NewPhysicalArchModule#% Function Prioritized by Generation functions and in which generation of %#NewPhysicalArchModule#% Function Prioritized by Generation design they will be implemented in. This approach is used to focus the team on ensuring that the critical functions get implemented first.
Each generation is planned such that the most important functionality is implemented in Gen 1 and Gen 2. In practicality Gen 4 and Gen 5 could be combined to accelerate schedule and certain functions might not get implemented.
Contained here in are the function diagrams and function descriptions.

This diagram shows the prioritization of the %#NewPhysicalArchModule#% Use Cases by generation. This approach is used to focus the simplest behaviors for implementation first tn ensure that the critical functions implemented have the right behaviors.
Each generation is planned such that the easiest to implement use cases are implemented in Gen 1 and Gen 2. In practicality Gen 4 and Gen 5 could be combined or canceled if the users determine the behaviors have been fulfilled by previous generations.
